{
  "text": "Similar findings linking AMPK activity with ␣Syn expression have been noted in models with genetically-induced ␣Syn overexpression. In PC12 cells overexpressing ␣Syn, resveratrol reduced ␣Syn, and this effect was blocked by knockdown of Beclin-1 or lysosomal inhibition, suggesting that increased macroautophagy was essential for resveratrol-induced clearance of ␣Syn [CITATION_1] . Similarly, PC12 cells incubated in cell media from ␣Syn overexpressing cells also had decreased viability and lower AMPK activity, but they could be rescued by activating AMPK with AICAR or metformin [CITATION_2] . In rats, ␣Syn overexpression decreased the number of SNc DA neurons, while overexpression of the ␣ subunit of AMPK or AMPK-CA ameliorated neuronal loss and deceased ␣Syn [CITATION_3] . Likewise, ␣Syn overexpression in retinoic acid differentiated SH-SY5Y cells increased cell death and decreased AMPK activity [CITATION_4] . Treatment with AICAR or metformin was neuroprotective in these cells and in cells incubated with cell media containing secreted ␣Syn or recombinant ␣Syn oligomers. Conversely, cells with AMPK knocked down via shRNA were more vulnerable to ␣Syn-induced cell death [CITATION_5] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "15226404",
